The d-c-a exam, prep tactics, and where to go next.

The whole course has been quietly building to this: the Docker Certified Associate, and its six domains map almost one-to-one onto the modules you've done.

The exam is administered by Mirantis. It's fifty-five questions, in ninety minutes, online-proctored, with a passing score around sixty-five to seventy percent, valid for two years. And the domains, with their weights, are just this course, reorganised. Orchestration is about twenty-five percent; that's module nine. Image creation and registry is about twenty percent; modules two and seven. Installation and configuration is about fifteen percent; that's this module, module ten. Networking is about fifteen percent; module five. Security is about fifteen percent; module eight. And storage and volumes is about ten percent; module four. So preparing is really just consolidating the course you've done; orchestration and images together are about forty-five percent of the exam.

Now, what to memorise, since there are no man pages in the exam: the shape of docker run and its common flags; volume versus bind-mount versus t-m-p-f-s semantics; when containers resolve each other by name, and the Swarm routing-mesh model; the docker file quirks, like command versus entry-point, copy versus add, and env versus arg; services versus tasks, and the rolling-update flags; and the Compose and stack deploy-block keys. What to look up at test time: the rarely-used daemon dot j-son keys, and profile paths. And above all, practise, don't just read; spin up a real three-node Swarm, with Multipass or Lima virtual machines, and run service create, scale, update, and rollback, and stack deploy, until they're muscle memory.

Where to go next. The natural path is Kubernetes; it orchestrates the same o-c-i images, with a richer model, and module nine's mapping makes the jump concrete: a service becomes a deployment, a task becomes a pod, a stack becomes a Helm chart. C-k-a-d, at the app level, is the right cert after d-c-a, then c-k-a, for the cluster, then c-k-s, for security. Or go cloud-specific, with e-c-s and e-k-s, cloud run and g-k-e, or a-k-s, if your work lives on one platform. Either way, you now hold the whole model: image, to container, to network, to volume, to registry, hardened, and orchestrated. And you can install, configure, debug, and certify it. That's the entire Docker platform, and you've built it up, one map at a time.
